    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose to spectrally and spatially resolve the intricated disk interactions in SR24 (a.k.a HBC262), a multiple protoplanetary disk system, with ALMA. SR 24 is a nearby (120pc) dynamically rich and complex system that contains two disks (North and South components) connected by a bridge seen in scattered light, and a extended plume. Cycle 2 observations will allow us to make progress on understanding the effect that dynamical interactions and binarity have on disk structure and consequently on planet formation. These data will help build a comprehensive picture of the gas and dust dynamics in multiple systems. Previous sub-mm observations focused only on SR24S and had poor sensitivity, unable to detect neither the bridge nor the extended plume. The northern disk is bright in 12CO emission but the dust continuum has not been detected. Previous data lack the require spectral resolution to understand SR24's dynamics. 
We aim to map SR24's and determine their disks radii (presumably truncated) and compare with theoretical predictions. Kinematic information given by ALMA's superb sensitivity and resolution will allow us to build a coherent three dimensional picture.</prp:abstract>
